On our Jira Cloud install, when I try to savea kanban subfilter, I'll get the following error message:
{code:none}
Unrecognized field "section" (Class com.atlassian.greenhopper.web.rapid.view.SubqueryEntry), not marked as ignorable at [Source: org.apache.catalina.connector.CoyoteInputStream@10b92eb; line: 1, column: 13] (through reference chain: com.atlassian.greenhopper.web.rapid.view.SubqueryEntry["section"])
{code}

Trying to save this JQL:
{noformat}
(fixVersion in unreleasedVersions() OR fixVersion is EMPTY) AND issuetype != Constant AND issuetype != Epic
{noformat}

This is the board/jira cloud install:
https://prefer.atlassian.net/secure/RapidView.jspa?rapidView=51

As per the following document ([Connecting JIRA to Oracle|https://confluence.atlassian.com/display/JIRA/Connecting+JIRA+to+Oracle], JIRA needs the Oracle user to have the following permissions to work properly:

{noformat}
GRANT CONNECT TO <user>;
GRANT CREATE TABLE TO <user>;
GRANT CREATE SEQUENCE TO <user>;
GRANT CREATE TRIGGER TO <user>;
{noformat}

It is stated, then, that either more or less permission will cause JIRA to present failure of functionalities and not work properly:

{quote}
If the incorrect permissions (either less or more than required) are applied, it's possible that some JIRA functions do not work properly, as described in this article.
{quote}

It would be great if there was an explanation of why the needed permission are what they are and what happens when more (or less) than needed permissions are present. The article linked only presents one example of this case.

